ing from the early Cold War to the Reagan years to the War on Terror demonstrate, grand strategy can be an immensely rewarding undertaking—but also one that is full of potential pitfalls on the long road between conception and implementation. Brands concludes by offering valuable suggestions for how American leaders might approach the challenges of grand strategy in the years to come.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 4aInternational Studies. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 4aU.S. History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh  a20th century history.  a20th century.  aAmerican leaders.  aAmerican politics.  aAmerican statecraft.  aCivil rights.  aCold War.  aPresidential strategy.  aReagan administration.  aarms control.  aborder security.  abush.  acold war.  aconflict.  acounterterrorism.  adefense.  adiplomacy.  aespionage.  aforeign policy.  aglobal affairs Truman.  agovernance.  agrand strategy.  ainternational relations.  apolitical science.  au.s. foreign policy.  awar on terror .08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060674440uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080147028840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801470288423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801470288/original  a978-3-11-060674-4  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles